tjceu.quest.db.1.title=Mining in Gregtech
tjceu.quest.db.1.desc=Gregtech ore veins generate thousands of ores in a roughly 4 square chunk area. Instead of mining a couple hundred vanilla iron veins, you'll likely %nwant to mine a single magnetite or limonite vein for an equivlent amount of iron. %n%nKeep in mind that there are over a hundred ore types, each representing a new mineral or element. Right now, the vast majority of these ores will be %nuseless to you, so use your prospector to find the veins you really want. %n%nGregtech also has some advanced ore-processing, which you don't need to get into at this point. If you're really desperate to increase yeild, you can make a couple of steam grinders and manually wash the impure dust they produce by throwing stacks of it into a cauldron.
tjceu.quest.db.2.title=Hammering enchant
tjceu.quest.db.2.desc=If you want to put hammering on the given hammer, it will allow you to condense different types of ore varients (ie: stone and diorite) into their crushed varients at the expense of more inventory clutter. It's your choice. %n%nWhile fortune does work with this enchant, it is capped at a max of 2x the drop amount to keep it balanced with the macerator.%n %n§4Crushed ore must be broken down again with a GT hard hammer to receive impure ore dust.%nResulting in nuggets instead of ingots.%nIt is not advised you use this enchant until you can smelt ore fast.
tjceu.quest.db.3.title=Basic Backpack
tjceu.quest.db.3.desc=A backpack can help carry all the tools you just made
tjceu.quest.db.4.title=Crafting Station
tjceu.quest.db.4.desc=
tjceu.quest.db.5.title=/dev/null/
tjceu.quest.db.5.desc=A dev/Null can help keep stone out of your inventory while mining.%n%nEach slot of the null can hold 256 items. matching items past that number are voided. This can be useful for mining but don't put building blocks in here
tjceu.quest.db.6.title=Scanner and prospector
tjceu.quest.db.6.desc=The 'Start of a long journey' quest provides a scanner, as well as a prospector. To use the scanner, right click while holding it. To change which cards are active, shift right click with the scanner in hand. To use the prospector, right click and it will reveal the ore content in the surrounding 3x3 chunks. This prospector has infinite uses, but has limited range and cannot detect fluid veins.
tjceu.quest.db.7.title=GregTech Axe
tjceu.quest.db.7.desc=Gregtech axes will chop the entire tree and will seek out neighboring wood blocks. This can sometimes result in forests being mined by one swing.
tjceu.quest.db.8.title=The start of a long journey
tjceu.quest.db.8.desc=%nWelcome to Technological Journey! Smack a tree a few times for some nice gear.
tjceu.quest.db.9.title=Sticky Resin
tjceu.quest.db.9.desc=Sap. Yummy.%n%nIf you can't find a rubber tree, go to the mining dimension. I highly suggest placing your rubber trees on the ground in a big patch, then making gregtech axes and chopping them all at once.
tjceu.quest.db.10.title=Steam Compressor
tjceu.quest.db.10.desc=You'll need to compress wood pulp into planks, resin into rubber, as well as fireclay into firebricks.
tjceu.quest.db.11.title=Red Alloy
tjceu.quest.db.11.desc=It's red, and it's an alloy. Redpower 2 users are turning in their tombs right now.
tjceu.quest.db.12.title=Early Power
tjceu.quest.db.12.desc=Steam will be your method of power production for a little bit. While buffering steam is discouraged, it may not be a bad idea now that you can make a super tank (32,000 buckets). It is also probably a good idea to put this steam in an ender tank so that you can route it anywhere - even remote miners in other dimensions.
tjceu.quest.db.13.title=1x Red Alloy Cable
tjceu.quest.db.13.desc=While this says it conducts ULV power, there is nothing in the game that generates or uses ULV power (other than transformers). Like the tin cables you made earlier, this is a crafting ingredient for now.
tjceu.quest.db.14.title=Tree Beacon
tjceu.quest.db.14.desc=Tired of chopping down trees? Then try a tree beacon. Grow a tree around and the beacon will absorb it, Then periodically drop logs. Will also drop other drops from the trees used like apples, rubber, or ectoplasm.
tjceu.quest.db.15.title=Ender Fluid Conduit
tjceu.quest.db.15.desc=Conduits are your best bet for moving items and fluids right now as they are relatively cheap, easy to setup, and quite flexible.
tjceu.quest.db.16.title=Small Steam Solid Fuel Boiler
tjceu.quest.db.16.desc=Single block steam boilers will autoput steam into adjacent machines. In addition, steam machines will not accept steam from the bottom. %n%nDon't worry about automating a water supply for this right now - it would be impressive to consume more than 16 buckets of water before you're able to make the endervoir. Just use a bucket, this isn't GTNH.
tjceu.quest.db.17.title=Copper Dust
tjceu.quest.db.17.desc=You'll want to use a mortar to grind up your copper ingots into dust. These break VERY fast, so either use flint as a cheap material or wrought iron so they last as long as possible.
tjceu.quest.db.18.title=Multiblock Builder
tjceu.quest.db.18.desc=The freedom wrench is very useful for building & debugging multiblocks. It can be used to rotate controllers to build multiblocks in unconventional %norientations (shift right click on controller), or to either preview, build or debug multiblock structures (right click on controller). To change mode, shift right click the air. %n%nNote: The build function does not work with tiered components, which must be placed by hand. It will also not magically know what hatch and bus layout you want.
tjceu.quest.db.19.title=Primitive Alloy Smelter
tjceu.quest.db.19.desc=Combining dusts might be good enough for bronze, but for more advanced alloys (like pulsating iron and red alloy) you need to combine materials %nunder pressure and high heat. The Steam Alloy Smelter (SAS) consumes steam and combines materials together. %n%nThis may be your first true GT multiblock, so this quest will also provide a description of how they work: %n%nThe structure requires at least 2 input busses, 1 input hatch, and 1 output bus. Your input items (redstone and copper) go into the two input busses, steam goes in the input hatch, and red alloy comes out the output bus.%n%n Later on, you can make LV input busses which have four slots, so if you wanted to you could replace one of the ULV input busses with an LV one and the other with more firebricks. This would allow you to dump all inputs in the same inventory.
tjceu.quest.db.20.title=Steam Motor (ULV)
tjceu.quest.db.20.desc=Moving things (in a circle) with the power of steam!
tjceu.quest.db.21.title=Compressed Fireclay
tjceu.quest.db.21.desc=You will need 132 compressed fireclay, 32 of which you'll get as a reward. Get macerating!
tjceu.quest.db.22.title=High Pressure Steam Forge Hammer
tjceu.quest.db.22.desc=Making plates at a 3-2 ratio! You'll get access to a 1-1 ratio in LV with the bending machine.
tjceu.quest.db.23.title=Steam Grinder
tjceu.quest.db.23.desc=This will run eight recipes every 30 seconds, which makes it faster than any singleblock macerator until HV. Consider setting a few of them up to handle ore processing for a while.%n%nThe steam hatch must be filled with steam for this to run, and it consumes steam as it processes, which means it's possible to run out in the middle of a craft. Make sure your steam supply is consistent & fast before you make this.
tjceu.quest.db.24.title=Time in a bottle
tjceu.quest.db.24.desc=This item will allow the steam age to progress much faster, it can also be used on gregtech machines. It is important to not let your factory be centered around using this item.
tjceu.quest.db.25.title=Copper
tjceu.quest.db.25.desc=Copper can be found in large quantities in bornite veins, alongside iron in pyrite veins, and alongside stibnite in tetrahedrite veins. Several other veins contain copper as a tertiary or sparodic ore, and can be freely mined as you see fit. You'll need lots of copper for bronze, circuit components, and wires.
tjceu.quest.db.26.title=Vacuum Tube
tjceu.quest.db.26.desc=Computation? These aren't exactly top-of-the-line transistors, but they do the job. Put a few of them together and you can make some nice new circuits.
tjceu.quest.db.27.title=Endervoir
tjceu.quest.db.27.desc=Finally, decent infinite water.
tjceu.quest.db.28.title=Chlorine
tjceu.quest.db.28.desc=
tjceu.quest.db.29.title=Aluminium
tjceu.quest.db.29.desc=
tjceu.quest.db.30.title=You're gonna... love this!
tjceu.quest.db.30.desc=These are components - you can read more about what each does in the `Covers + Simple Automation` quest directly above this. They are used in automation but also to craft various machines. This quest will accept any one of them, but if you make the pump, conveyer, and robot arm, you'll get a nice reward from the aforementioned quest. %n%nYou will have to make a version these for the majority of voltages. Good luck!
